    "summary": "Option B -- \"virtue\" in Laozi quote, \"character\" in author's analysis",
    "content": "**Option B.**\n\nThe Laozi passage is a *quotation* of a canonical text. Readers who know this passage in English know it with \"virtue.\" Using \"(constitutive) character\" in the block quote would make the reader think they are reading an unfamiliar text rather than recognizing DDJ Ch. 38. Recognition matters here -- the author's argument gains force precisely because the reader already has the conventional reading in mind and then watches the author dismantle it.\n\nThe switch from \"virtue\" in the block quote to \"character\" in the author's analysis actually *enacts* the author's philosophical move. The reader sees the familiar \"virtue\" in the Laozi quote, then watches the author reinterpret 德 as something different -- \"character\" -- through the phenomenological reversal. The terminological shift mirrors the conceptual shift. A TN at the transition point makes this explicit: \"The author's analysis reinterprets 德 not as moral virtue but as constitutive character -- what makes a thing what it is. See glossary.\"\n\nThis also respects the 文言 convention we already established: classical quotations preserve their standard rendering; the author's modern analysis uses our translation decisions."
  }
}
